3\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 3:16) What does this account teach you about\u160?...\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 \u8226? any attempt made to thwart God\u8217?s purpose?\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 \u8226? the means by which God might help us?\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 \u8226? courage?\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [End of inserted reference material or article.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 23:12, 13, 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 6\u8212?A plot to murder Paul was foiled (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ai\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\i bt}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 -E 191 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 paragraphs 5-6}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 )\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li660 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [Inserted scriptures.] Acts 23:12, 13: When it became day, the Jews formed a conspiracy and bound themselves with a curse, saying that they would neither eat nor drink until they had killed Paul. There were more than 40\u160?men who formed this oath-bound conspiracy.\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Acts 23:16: However, the son of Paul\u8217?s sister heard of the ambush they were planning, and he entered the soldiers\u8217? quarters and reported it to Paul. [End of inserted scriptures.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li576 \par\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Inserted Reference\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 5 The encouragement given Paul was timely. The very next day, over 40\u160?Jewish men \u8220?formed a conspiracy and bound themselves with a curse, saying they would neither eat nor drink until they had killed Paul.\u8221? This \u8220?oath-bound conspiracy\u8221? showed just how determined those Jews were to murder the apostle. If they did not succeed in carrying out their plot, the end result, they believed, would be a curse, or an evil, to them. (Acts 23:12-15) Their plan, sanctioned by the chief priests and older men, was to have Paul brought back to the Sanhedrin for further questioning, as if to ascertain matters concerning him more accurately. But en route, the conspirators would be lying in wait to pounce on Paul and kill him.\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 6 Paul\u8217?s nephew, however, heard of this plot and reported it to Paul. In turn, Paul had the young man report it to the Roman military commander Claudius Lysias. (Acts 23:16-22) Surely Jehovah loves young ones who, like this unnamed nephew of Paul, courageously put the welfare of God\u8217?s people ahead of their own and faithfully do whatever they can to promote Kingdom interests.\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [End of inserted reference material or article.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 24:2, 5, 6}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 \u8212?A public speaker named Tertullus made accusations against Paul to the Roman governor (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ai\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\i bt}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 -E 192 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 paragraph 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 0)\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li660 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [Inserted scriptures.] Acts 24:2: When he was called, Tertullus started accusing him, saying: \u8220?Seeing that we enjoy great peace through you and that through your forethought reforms are taking place in this nation,\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Acts 24:5, 6: For we have found this man to be a pest, stirring up seditions among all the Jews throughout the inhabited earth, and he is a spearhead of the sect of the Nazarenes. He also tried to profane the temple, so we seized him. [End of inserted scriptures.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li576 \par\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Inserted Reference\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 In Caesarea, Paul was \u8220?kept under guard in the praetorian palace of Herod\u8221? to await the arrival of the accusers from Jerusalem. (Acts 23:35) Five days later, they came\u8212?High Priest Ananias, a public speaker named Tertullus, and a group of older men. Tertullus first praised Felix for what he was doing for the Jews, evidently to flatter him and gain his favor. Then, getting to the matter at hand, Tertullus referred to Paul as \u8220?a pestilent fellow and stirring up seditions among all the Jews throughout the inhabited earth and a spearhead of the sect of the Nazarenes, one who also tried to profane the temple and whom we seized.\u8221? The other Jews \u8220?joined in the attack, asserting that these things were so.\u8221? (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 24:5, 6, 9}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 ) Stirring up sedition, spearheading a dangerous sect, and profaning the temple\u8212?these were serious charges that could result in a sentence of death.\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [End of inserted reference material or article.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 4:10-21\u8212?Paul respectfully denied the accusations and boldly gave a witness (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ai\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\i bt}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 -E 193-194 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 paragraphs 13-14}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 )\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li660 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [Inserted scripture.] Acts 24:10-21: When the governor nodded to Paul to speak, he answered: \u8220?Knowing well that this nation has had you as judge for many years, I readily speak in my own defense. As you can verify for yourself, it has not been more than 12\u160?days since I went up to worship in Jerusalem; and they found me neither arguing with anyone in the temple nor stirring up a mob, either in the synagogues or throughout the city. Nor can they prove to you the things they are accusing me of right now. But I do admit this to you, that according to the way that they call a sect, in this manner I am rendering sacred service to the God of my forefathers, as I believe all the things set forth in the Law and written in the Prophets. And I have hope toward God, which hope these men also look forward to, that there is going to be a resurrection of both the righteous and the unrighteous. Because of this I always strive to maintain a clear conscience before God and men. Now after quite a number of years, I arrived to bring gifts of mercy to my nation and to make offerings. While I was caring for these matters, they found me ceremonially cleansed in the temple, but not with a crowd or causing a disturbance. But there were some Jews from the province of Asia who ought to be present before you to accuse me if they actually have anything against me. Or let the men here say for themselves what wrong they found as I stood before the Sanhedrin, except for this one thing that I cried out while standing among them: \u8216?Over the resurrection of the dead I am today being judged before you!\u8217?\u8221? [End of inserted scripture.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li576 \par\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Inserted Reference\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 13 Paul set a good example for us to follow if we are ever brought before secular authorities because of our worship and are falsely accused of such things as being rabble-rousers, seditionists, or members of a \u8220?dangerous sect.\u8221? Paul did not fawn over the governor, uttering words of flattery as did Tertullus. Paul stayed calm and respectful. Tactfully, he gave clear and truthful testimony. Paul mentioned that the \u8220?Jews from the district of Asia\u8221? who had accused him of defiling the temple were not present and that legally, he should be able to face them and hear their accusations.\u8212?}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 24:18, 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 9.\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 14 Most strikingly, Paul did not hold back from giving testimony regarding his beliefs. Boldly, the apostle reiterated his belief in the resurrection, the issue that had created such turmoil when he was before the Sanhedrin. (Acts 23:6-10) In his defense, Paul emphasized the resurrection hope. Why? Because Paul was bearing witness to Jesus and to His resurrection from the dead\u8212?something those opposers would not accept. (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 26:6-8, 22, 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 3) Yes, it was the issue of the resurrection\u8212?and more precisely, belief in Jesus and in his resurrection\u8212?on which the controversy was centered.\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltr